<h2>Password Managers: The Practical Solution</h2>

<p>
  The reality is that no human can remember 100+ unique, high-entropy passwords. Password managers solve this by generating and storing unique passwords for every account, encrypted behind one master password.
</p>

<p>
  For developers, password managers also handle:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>API keys and tokens</strong> — Store them securely instead of in plaintext config files.</li>
  <li><strong>SSH keys and passphrases</strong> — Keep SSH key passphrases accessible without sticky notes.</li>
  <li><strong>Database credentials</strong> — Especially for local development environments.</li>
  <li><strong>TOTP secrets</strong> — Many password managers also handle 2FA codes.</li>
</ul>

